<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-07-08T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-07-08T05:00:00-05:00" n="1033" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1033">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">711.93 Tibet/7–849: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-07-08T18:00:00+08:00">July 8, 1949—6
                                p. m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received 6:26 p. m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1459. We like suggestion Embassy, New Delhi, to send small mission this
                        summer to Lhasa (Department’s intel July 5, 1 a. m.<note n="16" xml:id="d1033fn16">Not printed.</note>). Authority Canton Government
                        over Tibet non-existent and we agree any move with implications recognition
                        autonomous status Tibet should be made before relations established with
                        Chinese Communist government.</p>
                    <p>Sent Department 1459, repeated New Delhi 6.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>